Phase 1 · Multi-Agent AI Career Copilot

1. System Architecture
The two diagrams above show the full picture. Here is the written breakdown.
The system has four distinct layers. The React frontend handles all user interaction — file uploads, JD text entry, GitHub URL input, and the results dashboard. It talks exclusively to the FastAPI backend, which owns authentication, file storage, job dispatch, and all API responses. The backend triggers the LangGraph Orchestrator as a background job; the orchestrator manages the agent pipeline and writes results back to PostgreSQL. The frontend polls for completion and renders results when the job is done.
External integrations are two: the Gemini API (or OpenAI behind an abstraction layer), called by each agent that needs an LLM, and the GitHub REST/GraphQL API, called only by the GitHub agent.

2. LangGraph Workflow
The graph has the following nodes and edges:
START → ingestion_node → [resume_node, jd_node, github_node] → ats_node → aggregator_node → END
Key routing decisions:
ingestion_node performs a conditional edge: if any input is invalid (PDF unreadable, GitHub URL 404), it routes to error_node and terminates early with a user-readable error payload. Otherwise it fans out.
resume_node and jd_node run in parallel. ats_node has a conditional wait: it only executes after both resume_node and jd_node have written their outputs to shared state. github_node runs in parallel with resume and JD and does not block ATS.
Every agent node has retry logic (max 3 attempts, exponential backoff) before it routes to error_node with partial state. The aggregator handles partial state gracefully — if one agent failed, it reports a partial score and flags which section is unavailable.

