    status: str = "pending"     # pending | running | completed | failed

4. Agent Responsibilities
Resume Analysis Agent
The agent calls an LLM with the full extracted PDF text. The system prompt instructs it to return a JSON object conforming to ResumeData. Before passing text to the LLM, a pre-processing step uses pdfplumber to extract raw text, preserving section headers. The agent also runs a deterministic post-processing pass: it scores bullet points for action verbs against a curated verb list (achieved, built, optimized, reduced, etc.) and flags bullets with no numbers as missing quantification. These rule-based checks are not left to the LLM.
Job Description Agent
Receives raw JD text. Uses an LLM call with a structured extraction prompt returning JDData. Runs a secondary NLP pass using spaCy (or simple regex) to extract technology names not captured by the LLM. No external API calls.
ATS Evaluation Agent
This agent runs after both resume and JD data are in state. It does not make a single LLM call with both documents — that approach produces vague output. Instead:

Keyword Match: deterministic set intersection between resume_data.extracted_technologies + resume_data.skills and jd_data.important_keywords. Score = matched / total × 100.
Required Skills Match: same method against jd_data.required_skills.
Preferred Skills Match: same method against jd_data.preferred_skills, weighted 0.5×.
Completeness Score: checks for presence of education, experience, projects, skills sections. Rule-based.
Project Relevance: LLM call — pass jd_data.technologies and resume_data.projects, ask for a relevance score with explanation.
Action Verb Score: len(weak_bullets) / total_bullets ratio, inverted.
Quantification Score: regex scan for numbers/percentages in bullets.

The final overall_score is a weighted average: keyword match (25%), required skills (30%), preferred skills (10%), completeness (10%), project relevance (15%), action verbs (5%), quantification (5%).
Every sub-score gets a human-readable explanation stored in score_explanations. This is what makes the output genuinely useful rather than a black-box number.
GitHub Intelligence Agent
Input is either a username or a repo URL. The agent normalizes it to a username first. It then makes the following GitHub API calls:

GET /users/{username} — profile metadata
GET /users/{username}/repos?sort=updated&per_page=30 — repository list
GET /users/{username}/events/public?per_page=100 — commit activity
GraphQL: pinnedItems query to get pinned repositories (REST API does not expose pinned repos)
For each repo in pinned set: GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/readme — README presence and length check
GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/contents — check for Dockerfile, docker-compose.yml, .github/workflows, screenshots folder

The agent then calls the LLM with all collected structured data and asks it to generate GitHubData.portfolio_feedback and improvement_suggestions. Raw scores (repo quality, diversity, activity) are computed deterministically from the API data.
Repo quality scoring (per repo, averaged): stars (max 20 pts), has README > 200 words (20 pts), has description (10 pts), has deployment evidence (15 pts), has CI workflow (10 pts), updated in last 6 months (15 pts), has screenshots/demo link (10 pts).

5. Backend Architecture
FastAPI Application
├── /auth                     JWT-based auth (register, login, refresh)
├── /upload                   PDF upload endpoint → stores to /tmp or S3
├── /analyze                  POST: creates analysis job, enqueues to Celery
├── /jobs/{job_id}            GET: poll job status + results
├── /reports/{job_id}         GET: full final report JSON
└── /health                   Healthcheck

Services Layer
├── LLMService                Wraps Gemini/OpenAI, unified interface
├── PDFService                pdfplumber extraction
├── GitHubService             GitHub API client with rate limit handling
├── JobService                Creates/updates job records
└── ReportService             Assembles final report from state

LangGraph runs inside Celery worker
The LangGraph graph is compiled once at application startup and cached. Each analysis job creates a new state instance and invokes graph.astream() inside the Celery task. Results are written to PostgreSQL incrementally as agents complete — the frontend polling endpoint returns partial data as it arrives.

